<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:id="@+id/widget_root"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:background="@drawable/widget_background"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    android:padding="16dp">

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:text="Quick Add"
        android:textColor="#FFFFFF"
        android:textSize="16sp"
        android:textStyle="bold"
        android:layout_marginBottom="8dp" />

    <!-- 
       NOTE: Android Widgets have very limited support for input.
       AppWidgetHostView does NOT support EditText well in many launchers, 
       and it's complex to get the text back without user interaction.
       
       Simpler Approach:
       Just a 'Launch' button logic for now? 
       OR we use a pending intent to launch an activity that is transparent to get input.
       
       HOWEVER, the user asked for "Input of Transaction".
       
       Standard approach for this in Flutter home_widget:
       Usually we don't do full input form in widget. We launch the app.
       IF we want input on widget, we need to use RemoteViews and maybe a specific PendingIntent.
       EditText is theoretically supported but often buggy in widgets.
       
       Let's try a standard click-to-open approach first, 
       OR a preset buttons approach? 
       
       Wait, let's try to stick to the plan: "Type amount in widget".
       This is hard to do reliably in standard widgets. 
       
       BETTER UX: 
       A layout that looks like an input, but clicking it opens the app 
       with keyboard auto-focused on the amount field. 
       This is robust.
       
       Let's implement a clean "Plus" button that opens the QuickAdd sheet directly.
       And maybe 3 shortcuts: "Food", "Transport", etc? (Too complex for dynamic user data).
       
       Let's stick to a clean "Add Transaction" button widget for now that deep links 
       directly to the add sheet.
       
       Wait, the user EXPLICITLY said "needs input of Transaction".
       If I cannot do EditText reliably, I should probably do a "Quick Add" button 
       that launches the app immediately to the input screen.
       
       Let's add a visual text input that is clickable but actually launches the app.
    -->

    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:background="#FFFFFF"
        android:orientation="horizontal"
        android:padding="8dp"
        android:id="@+id/input_container"
        android:clickable="true">
        
        <TextView
            android:layout_width="0dp"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:layout_weight="1"
            android:text="Tap to enter amount..."
            android:textColor="#757575"
            android:textSize="14sp" />

        <ImageView
            android:layout_width="24dp"
            android:layout_height="24dp"
            android:src="@android:drawable/ic_input_add"
            android:tint="#000000" />
            
    </LinearLayout>

</LinearLayout>
